                    conversationalText = "In children with congenital heart disease (CHD) undergoing noncardiac surgery, carefully analyze shunt direction (L-to-R vs. R-to-L), presence of obstruction (AS, TOF), and the balance between pulmonary (PVR) and systemic vascular resistance (SVR). In left-to-right shunts (ASD, VSD, PDA), high SVR and low PVR increase shunt volume and heart failure. In right-to-left shunts (TOF), a drop in SVR or rise in PVR (hypoxia, hypercapnia, acidosis, pain) increases the shunt, triggering a hypercyanotic spell (tet spell). Meticulously avoid air bubbles in IV lines due to risk of paradoxical systemic embolization.",
