                    conversationalText = "In Postoperative Nausea and Vomiting (PONV) rescue therapy, the fundamental rule is to choose an agent from a different drug class than the prophylactic agent used. According to the Fourth Consensus Guidelines: 1. If a 5-HT3 antagonist (e.g., Ondansetron) was administered during induction/surgery and PONV occurs within the first 6 hours postoperatively, do not repeat the dose; rescue with a different class (e.g., Droperidol/Haloperidol, Metoclopramide, Dexmedetomidine, or sub-hypnotic Propofol 10-20 mg in the PACU). 2. Prophylactic agents (including Ondansetron) may be repeated only if PONV occurs > 6 hours postoperatively. Optimize hydration and limit opioids.",
