                    conversationalText = "Antibiotic dose adjustments in renal failure must be tailored based on the drug's pharmacokinetics, infection severity, level of renal impairment (eGFR/CrCl), dialysis status, and patient weight. 1. Calculate eGFR or creatinine clearance using the most recent creatinine value. 2. The initial loading dose must be administered in full, regardless of renal function, in patients with severe sepsis or for surgical prophylaxis, as achieving rapid therapeutic levels is critical. 3. Reduce subsequent maintenance doses or prolong dosing intervals according to renal function guidelines. 4. Utilize therapeutic drug monitoring (TDM) for drugs with a narrow therapeutic index, such as vancomycin and aminoglycosides (e.g., gentamicin). 5. Factors like obesity, sepsis (increased volume of distribution), burns, and renal replacement therapies (hemodialysis/CRRT) significantly alter dosing requirements. 6. For surgical prophylaxis, intraoperative redosing (e.g., cefazolin) is required if the procedure is prolonged or blood loss exceeds 1500 mL, even in patients with renal failure.",
