                    conversationalText = "Rapid vancomycin infusion can cause a non-immunologic reaction formerly known as 'Red Man Syndrome' (Vancomycin Infusion Reaction), driven by direct, rate-dependent histamine release from mast cells. Symptoms typically begin 10-20 minutes after starting the infusion and include flushing, pruritus, and burning of the face, neck, and upper torso, occasionally accompanied by systemic hypotension. This is not an IgE-mediated true allergy, but it must be carefully distinguished from anaphylaxis. Management: 1. Stop the vancomycin infusion immediately (or reduce the rate by 50% for mild reactions). 2. Assess ABCs, blood pressure, and check for bronchospasm or laryngeal edema. 3. Administer H1/H2 antihistamines (e.g., pheniramine) and supportive IV fluids. 4. If severe bronchospasm, stridor, airway edema, or refractory hypotension occurs, initiate the anaphylaxis protocol and do not delay epinephrine. 5. If vancomycin is required in the future, administer it much slower (minimum over 2 hours or < 10 mg/min) and consider antihistamine premedication.",
