            AiStructuredResponse(
                    safetyLevel = "urgent",
                    notASubstituteWarning = "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
                    conversationalText = "Following a suspected perioperative anaphylaxis/hypersensitivity event, the primary goal is to conclusively identify the culprit agent (e.g., neuromuscular blockers, antibiotics, chlorhexidine, latex) and find safe alternatives for future anesthetics. The ANZCA 2025 hypersensitivity guidelines emphasize a detailed allergy history, reviewing prior records, and modifying the anesthetic plan accordingly. During the acute event: 1. Collect serum tryptase samples at appropriate intervals (ideally at onset of reaction, 1-2 hours post-reaction, and a baseline sample at >24 hours). 2. Document all drugs administered, surgical exposures, and a precise timeline. 3. Provide the patient with written documentation of the event and refer them to an Allergy/Immunology specialist. Diagnostic skin and in-vitro testing are typically scheduled 4-6 weeks after the event to avoid false negatives due to mediator depletion. Any future anesthetic must be planned with specialist test results. ([ANZCA])",
