                    conversationalText = "Intraoperative awareness (accidental awareness under general anesthesia) is a serious complication that can cause severe psychological distress and PTSD. Awareness risk is significantly higher with TIVA, low-dose anesthesia, dose reductions due to hemodynamic instability (trauma, emergency obstetrics, cardiac surgery), use of neuromuscular blockers, history of awareness, and equipment or drug delivery errors. Prevention strategies: 1. Systematically check the anesthesia machine, vaporizer level, infusion pumps, and IV access. 2. Ensure adequate hypnotic dosing to maintain appropriate depth of anesthesia. 3. Remember that when neuromuscular blockers are used, lack of patient movement does not prove adequate anesthesia. 4. In TIVA, frequently verify IV line patency, check for extravasation, and ensure connection security. 5. Processed EEG (e.g., BIS) may be considered in selected high-risk patients. The ASA practice advisory treats brain monitors as tools to be used based on risk factors and clinical context rather than as a mandatory routine for all patients. ([asahq.org])",
