                    referencesToShow = listOf("Anesthesiology: Burst Suppression During General Anesthesia. 2021.", "Miller's Anesthesia, 9th Edition.")
                ),
            AiStructuredResponse(
                    safetyLevel = "urgent",
                    notASubstituteWarning = "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
                    conversationalText = "A burst suppression pattern on the EEG is characterized by periods of high-voltage brain activity (bursts) alternating with periods of flat, isoelectric activity (suppression). This pattern reflects very deep hypnotic drug effects, severe hypothermia, cerebral hypoperfusion (low cerebral blood flow), metabolic disturbances (hypoglycemia, severe acidosis), or acute brain injury. 1. Immediately check anesthetic and sedative drug dosages and reduce excessive depth if indicated. 2. Quickly assess blood pressure (MAP), oxygenation (SpO2), ventilation (PaCO2), blood glucose, core temperature, and electrolytes. 3. Remember that in older and frail patients, excessively deep anesthesia and burst suppression are strongly linked to postoperative delirium and delayed emergence. 4. If burst suppression is not the clinical target, gradually reduce the hypnotic dose. 5. If intentionally induced for neuroprotection (e.g., status epilepticus, refractory ICP), the target Suppression Ratio (SR) and duration must be clearly defined. 6. Rule out technical or electrode-related artifacts.",
                    immediateRedFlags = listOf("EEG suppression ratio reaching 80-100%, indicating a near-isoelectric state.", "Deep systemic hypotension occurring alongside burst suppression, threatening cerebral perfusion.", "Sudden unexplained onset of burst suppression, raising suspicion of acute cerebral embolism or severe hypoxia."),
