                    referencesToShow = listOf("Anesthesia and perioperative pain relief in the frail elderly. PMC 2023.", "ESAIC Guideline on Postoperative Delirium. 2024.")
                ),
            AiStructuredResponse(
                    safetyLevel = "elective",
                    notASubstituteWarning = "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
                    conversationalText = "Postoperative Cognitive Dysfunction (POCD) and Postoperative Delirium risks are dramatically elevated in patients who are older (especially >65-70 years), frail, have baseline dementia or cognitive impairment, suffer from sensory loss (visual, auditory), take multiple medications (polypharmacy), and undergo major surgery (especially cardiac and major orthopedic). Frailty represents a state of vulnerability with reduced physiologic reserve, predisposing the patient to complications, functional decline, and cognitive vulnerability. Risk reduction: 1. Avoid deliriogenic drugs such as unnecessary benzodiazepines, anticholinergics (atropine, scopolamine), H1 blockers, and meperidine. 2. Provide optimal pain control using regional blocks and opioid-sparing multimodal regimens. 3. Prevent hypoxia, hypotension, hypoglycemia, dehydration, and sleep disruption. 4. Encourage early mobilization and immediately return glasses and hearing aids in the postoperative period. 5. Utilize frequent reorientation, family support, and a familiar environment. Any new-onset postoperative confusion must prompt screening for hidden infection (e.g., UTI), urinary retention, electrolyte imbalance, and acute drug effects. ([PMC])",
