                    conversationalText = "Frailty is a multidimensional clinical syndrome characterized by a decline in physiologic reserve across multiple organ systems, resulting in increased vulnerability to stressors. Anesthetic management of frail older patients requires meticulous planning because frailty significantly increases the risk of postoperative complications, delirium, permanent functional decline, prolonged hospital stays, and complex discharge needs. 1. Conduct a thorough preoperative assessment of baseline functional status, mobility, nutritional status, cognition, fall risk, and social support. 2. Administer all anesthetic and sedative agents in significantly reduced doses, titrate slowly, and anticipate prolonged drug effects. 3. Aggressively avoid intraoperative hypotension, hypoxia, hypothermia, and excessively deep anesthesia (burst suppression). 4. Utilize regional anesthesia techniques and plan opioid-sparing multimodal analgesia. 5. Plan early mobilization, physiotherapy, and structured delirium prevention. 6. Coordinate postoperative intermediate or ICU care and discharge planning preoperatively.",
