                    notASubstituteWarning = "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
                    conversationalText = "Older patients exhibit significantly increased sensitivity to anesthetic agents due to age-related physiological changes (decreased cardiac output, increased body fat ratio, reduced hepatic and renal blood flow, and increased brain receptor sensitivity). This fundamentally alters the pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic profiles of sedatives, opioids, hypnotics, and neuromuscular blockers. Safe dosing strategies: 1. Use significantly lower starting doses and titrate slowly (induction doses should generally be reduced by 30% to 50%). 2. Allow extra time for drugs to reach their site of action (prolonged effect-site equilibration); avoid rapid repeated bolus injections (dose stacking). 3. Always check baseline renal and hepatic function (eGFR/CrCl). 4. Minimize or completely avoid benzodiazepine and anticholinergic drug burden to prevent postoperative delirium and cognitive decline. 5. Always utilize quantitative TOF monitoring to prevent residual neuromuscular blockade. 6. Monitor closely for hypotension, respiratory depression, delirium, and delayed emergence.",
