                    conversationalText = "Preoperative anemia is a strong, independent predictor of adverse postoperative outcomes, including increased morbidity, 30-day mortality, and blood transfusion requirements. Anemia screening should be performed prior to any elective surgery with an expected blood loss > 500 mL. The goal of preoperative patient blood management (PBM) is not merely to wait for a transfusion threshold, but to diagnose and actively treat the underlying cause. Check Hb, MCV, ferritin, transferrin saturation (TSAT), B12/folate, and renal function. Treat iron deficiency with oral or IV iron; IV iron is preferred if surgery is scheduled in < 3-4 weeks or if GI absorption is impaired. Erythropoietin (EPO) may be considered in chronic kidney disease or anemia of chronic disease. Inquire about active bleeding sources. Plan intraoperative blood conservation strategies (e.g., tranexamic acid, cell salvage, restrictive transfusion thresholds). In emergency cases, optimization is limited; focus on oxygen delivery and bleeding control.",
