                    conversationalText = "Bridging therapy when stopping warfarin involves a delicate balance between the patient's thromboembolic risk and the surgical bleeding risk. Routine bridging for all patients is no longer recommended (e.g., supported by the BRIDGE trial). High-thrombotic-risk conditions warranting bridging include: 1. Mechanical mitral valve prosthesis, 2. Older-generation or high-risk mechanical aortic valve prosthesis, 3. Stroke or transient ischemic attack (TIA) within the last 3 months, 4. Venous thromboembolism (VTE) within the last 3 months, 5. Severe thrombophilia states, 6. High-risk atrial fibrillation (e.g., CHA2DS2-VASc score >= 7-8). In patients with low-to-moderate thromboembolic risk, bridging increases bleeding complications without reducing thromboembolism. LMWH (e.g., enoxaparin) or UFH choice depends on renal function and surgical timing; restarting must be deferred until surgical hemostasis is fully secured (typically 24-72 hours post-op).",
