                    conversationalText = "The primary goal of fluid management in ERAS is to maintain euvolemia by avoiding both intravascular hypovolemia and fluid overload (hypervolemia). Traditional liberal fluid regimens cause tissue edema, impaired anastomotic healing, prolonged ileus, and pulmonary complications. Conversely, overly restrictive regimens can lead to organ hypoperfusion and acute kidney injury (AKI). Thus, ERAS promotes goal-directed fluid therapy (GDFT). GDFT involves titrating fluid boluses (250 mL of balanced crystalloids) based on dynamic parameters of fluid responsiveness, such as Stroke Volume (SV), Stroke Volume Variation (SVV), or Pulse Pressure Variation (PPV). If hypotension occurs due to anesthesia-induced vasodilation (e.g., neuraxial blocks), support the MAP early with low-dose vasopressors (e.g., norepinephrine) rather than infusing excessive crystalloids.",
