                    conversationalText = "The decision to postpone elective surgery should not be automatic simply because a clinical risk factor exists. The clinician must balance the modifiability of the risk within a short timeframe, the urgency of the surgical procedure (emergency, urgent, time-sensitive, vs. elective), and the progression risk of the primary surgical pathology if delayed. Postponement and active optimization are indicated for: active cardiac conditions (e.g., recent MI, unstable angina), severe uncontrolled hypertension with acute end-organ damage or symptoms (typically BP > 180/110 mmHg), decompensated heart failure, severe hypoxemia (SpO2 < 90% on room air), active lower respiratory tract infection, uncontrolled diabetic crises (DKA/HHS), suspected euglycemic DKA, severe uncorrected electrolyte abnormalities (e.g., K < 2.5 or K > 6.0 mEq/L), unexplained severe anemia (Hb < 8 g/dL), active uncontrolled sepsis, recent stroke within 3 months, severe unreversed coagulopathy, or the lack of a secure postoperative care/ICU plan. In emergency surgery, postponement is impossible; prioritize rapid risk mitigation, invasive monitoring, and ICU preparation.",
