                    conversationalText = "PECS (Pectoral Nerve Blocks) and Serratus Anterior Plane (SAP) blocks are fascial plane blocks designed to provide opioid-sparing analgesia for chest wall and breast surgeries.\n\nClinical Use:\n1. PECS I: Administered between pectoralis major and minor muscles. Targets the lateral and medial pectoral nerves.\n2. PECS II: Adds a second injection between pectoralis minor and serratus anterior muscles, blocking the intercostocutaneous nerves (T2-T6) and thoracodorsal nerve. Ideal for breast resections and axillary dissections.\n3. Serratus Anterior Plane Block: Administered superficial or deep to the serratus anterior muscle. Targets the lateral cutaneous branches of intercostal nerves. Useful for rib fracture pain and breast surgery.\n4. Risks: Rapid systemic absorption of local anesthetics from large fascial surfaces (LAST risk). Proximity to the chest wall carries pneumothorax risk. Compressibility varies with depth in anticoagulated patients.",
