                    conversationalText = "Adductor canal block (ACB) targets the saphenous nerve and the articular branches of the vastus medialis nerve within the adductor canal deep to the sartorius muscle at the mid-thigh. It is widely used for knee surgery analgesia (e.g. total knee arthroplasty).\n\nClinical Characteristics:\n1. Motor-Sparing Property: Preserves quadriceps motor strength (especially rectus femoris and vastus intermedius) much better than a femoral nerve block, facilitating early mobilization and active physical therapy.\n2. Limitations: Not purely motor-sparing. High volumes (e.g. > 20 mL) can cause proximal spread into the femoral triangle, resulting in quadriceps weakness.\n3. Analgesic Gaps: Excellent for anterior knee pain but does not cover posterior knee pain (sciatic nerve territory); should be combined with local infiltration analgesia (LIA) or systemic adjuvants.\n4. Risks: Inadvertent femoral vessel puncture (the saphenous nerve lies close to the artery in the canal), LAST, and hematoma.",
