                    conversationalText = "Ankle block is a superficial, safe, and compressible regional anesthesia option for surgeries of the distal foot and toes. It targets 5 distinct nerves at the level of the ankle:\n\n1. Tibial Nerve: Located behind the medial malleolus. Supplies the sole of the foot. It is the deepest nerve; avoid puncture of the adjacent posterior tibial artery.\n2. Deep Peroneal Nerve: Runs next to the anterior tibial artery beneath the extensor tendons. Supplies the first web space.\n3. Superficial Peroneal Nerve: Subcutaneous at the lateral malleolus. Supplies the dorsum of the foot.\n4. Sural Nerve: Subcutaneous between the lateral malleolus and the Achilles tendon. Covers the lateral border of the foot.\n5. Saphenous Nerve: Subcutaneous anterior to the medial malleolus. Covers the medial ankle.\n\nClinical Utility: Excellent safety profile with no deep bleeding or chest complications. However, it does not cover thigh or calf tourniquet pain; if a tourniquet is used, sedation or a more proximal block is required. Use caution in severe peripheral arterial disease or local infection.",
