                    conversationalText = "Epidural anesthesia and analgesia safety depends on selecting the correct anatomical level, strict adherence to anticoagulation guidelines, aseptic technique, test dose administration, fractionated dosing, and close clinical monitoring.\n\nSafety Protocols and Steps:\n1. Placement Documentation: Carefully document any paresthesia, blood return, or CSF leak during the procedure.\n2. Test Dose: Always aspirate before any injection. Use an epinephrine-containing test dose (e.g. 3 mL of 1.5% Lidocaine with 1:200,000 Epinephrine) to rule out accidental intravascular or intrathecal placement. Monitor for a heart rate spike or sudden motor block.\n3. Dosing: Always inject large volumes fractionally (3-5 mL increments) and slowly.\n4. Complication Monitoring: Monitor for hypotension, high block level, respiratory depression, and LAST.\n5. Epidural Hematoma: Any unexpected dense or progressive motor block, or new neurological deficit, requires immediate evaluation for epidural hematoma or catheter migration into the subarachnoid space.\n6. Catheter Removal: Catheter insertion and removal timing must follow ASRA anticoagulation protocols strictly.",
