                    conversationalText = "Hypotension after spinal anesthesia is caused by preganglionic sympathetic blockade, leading to widespread vasodilation (venous pooling) and a drop in systemic vascular resistance (SVR). High sympathetic block (T1-T4) can also cause concurrent bradycardia.\n\nEmergency Approach and Management:\n1. Assessment: Immediately assess blood pressure and heart rate.\n2. Left Uterine Displacement: In pregnant patients, ensure 15-degree left uterine displacement to prevent aortocaval compression.\n3. Position: Trendelenburg positioning may improve venous return (exercise caution to prevent block level from ascending too high).\n4. Fluid Bolus: Administer a rapid IV crystalloid or colloid bolus (co-loading is generally preferred over pre-loading).\n5. Vasopressors: Administer Phenylephrine (50-100 mcg IV bolus or titrated infusion) or Ephedrine (5-10 mg IV bolus). If bradycardia is present, Ephedrine is preferred.\n6. Bradycardia Management: Consider Atropine (0.5 mg IV) for significant bradycardia.\n7. Differential: Rule out hemorrhage, anaphylaxis, or primary cardiac events as causes of hypotension.",
