                    notASubstituteWarning = "This response does not replace clinical judgment. Base decisions on your clinical assessment.",
                    conversationalText = "High or total spinal is a life-threatening anesthesia emergency caused by excessive cephalad spread of local anesthetic within the subarachnoid space. Symptoms include rapidly ascending sensory and motor block, severe hypotension, bradycardia, arm numbness/weakness, dyspnea (due to intercostal and diaphragmatic paralysis), loss of speech (aphonia), and loss of consciousness.\n\nEmergency Management Protocol:\n1. Call for Help: Immediately call for emergency assistance / blue code.\n2. Oxygenation: Administer 100% Oxygen.\n3. Airway and Ventilation: Secure the airway immediately by endotracheal intubation if respiratory failure, aphonia, or loss of consciousness occurs, and initiate mechanical ventilation.\n4. Hemodynamic Support: Administer rapid IV fluid boluses and aggressive vasopressors (Ephedrine, Phenylephrine).\n5. Avoid Arrest: For severe bradycardia or imminent collapse, administer Atropine (0.5-1.0 mg) and do not delay initiating Epinephrine (10-100 mcg IV bolus, followed by titrated infusion).\n6. Pregnancy: Maintain left uterine displacement in obstetric patients.\n7. Continuous Care: Provide full ventilatory and hemodynamic support until the local anesthetic block regresses (typically 1.5 to 3 hours).",
